<h1>Background</h1>=20
<h2>Guide to Seattle</h2>=20
<p><em>Excerpted from "The Fire and the Future, Seattle in the 90s,and the =
decade that changed the world"</em></p>=20
<h3>1994 Cadabra is Born</h3>=20
<p>The second newest of the big four tech firms in Seattle, this retail gia=
nt was founded by Jeff &amp; MacKenzie in 1994. While their original plan m=
ay have been to sell books, they would quickly seize on the wave of awakeni=
ng in their backyard to propel their firm to the behemoth which runs half t=
he worlds websites, and delivers more packages then the USPS, DHL, and UPS =
combined. </p>=20
<h3>1995 IONS founded</h3>=20
<p>The most recent, and possibly most influential of the big four, IONS was=
 formally incorporated in 1995. It inherited the patents and groundbreaking=
 work of Michael Bertiaux and Howard Rheingold, which would form the basis =
of both the awakening, magic, and modern cybernetics today. CEO Willis Harm=
an then took the bold step of combining all of these patents into a single =
unified pool, with a fixed fee, open to anyone who wished to utilize the te=
chnology, setting the groundwork for the company=92s future wealth, and mak=
ing it into the R&amp;D giant that continues to be integral to most advance=
ments in technology today.</p>=20
<h3>1996 The Father of All Demos</h3>=20
<p>While the patents were filed and theoretically open to all a year earlie=
r, it was this presentation to a UW auditorium in July of 1996 which would =
set off the boom that subsequently consumed the world. Over the course of a=
n hour Willis Harman demonstrated both the finished Obsidian and Ruby impla=
nts, giving birth to the modern mages and hackers respectively, along with =
the first practical examples of cybernetic enhancement. While the broader p=
ublic would remain skeptical of both the truth and usefulness of these disc=
overies for years to come, the local business community was sold, kicking o=
ff the first boom. </p>=20
<h3>1999 United States v. Microsoft Corp.</h3>=20
<p>While the case itself was quickly overshadowed by Black December, the di=
vision of Microsoft would have massive implications for the local economy, =
and create the big four as we know them today. No longer shackled by having=
 to promote an operating system, the new Microsoft would rapidly expand int=
o new areas of growth, launching new ERP, finance, and multimedia software,=
 and becoming the omnipresent element of all of our lives. And Windows Corp=
, now left with one major stream of revenue, found itself forced to both ex=
pand its offerings for operating environments both larger servers, smaller =
mobile devices, and all manner of integrated applications in-between. Not t=
o mention the launch of their Portal cloud environments, making them integr=
al to the modern internet.</p>=20
<h3>1999 1/12 (Battle for Seattle)</h3>=20
<p>The WTO meetings in Seattle were contentious from the start. Even before=
 1/12 there was demonstrating, rioting, and pitched battles with police all=
 around the sites of the meetings. It was becoming increasing clear that th=
e police were losing control of the situation when Bill Clinton made the fa=
teful decision to attend the sessions on 1/12 in person. As the president e=
xited his convoy to a crowd of the worlds press, no one was expecting a man=
 to suddenly appear behind him holding a sword, let alone for that man to d=
ecapitate the sitting president and disappear just as suddenly. </p>=20
<p>It would take nearly a weak before it was clear that the anarchist and b=
lack block groups organizing the demonstrations were not responsible, but i=
nstead the awakened terrorists of the Invisible Committee. But in that time=
 the reaction was swift and harsh, with thousands being held without trial,=
 and nearly 10 blocks of downtown being heavily damaged or abandoned in the=
 ensuing clean up operations.<br></p>=20
<h3>1999 YTK</h3>=20
<p>The city was still in the early stages of recovery from the battle of Se=
attle, when the final chapter of Black December came to a close. In a matte=
r of minutes more then half the computers in the city were no longer operat=
ing, and 73% of the city found itself without power for nearly three days. =
While this further delayed the attempts to rebuild the city, more immediate=
ly this served as the final catalyst for President Gore to declare the war =
on terror, plunging the USA and Seattle into the 21st century. </p>=20
