<h2>Hacking</h2>=20
<p>This section outlines how hacking works in this setting. This primarily =
impacts characters playing hackers, but has implications for the general wa=
y computer networks work.</p>
<p>Each computer, camera, server, device is a 'node'. If you control the no=
de then you have access to all the data on it, and can give commands to it,=
 and anything controlled by it. Each node has a number of 'connections' whi=
ch link it to other nodes and the outside world. For example if you have a =
machine that controls security cameras, it might have a physical port that =
is a connection, a line connection to the server in the building, and a con=
nection to the public internet. All abilities or attempts to influence a ma=
chine require you to use one of these connections. If it is physical, you n=
eed to be plugged in, or in wifi range, if it is to the net you need to hav=
e access to the internet, and if it is to another system, you need to eithe=
r control or occupy that system. A hacker is in the most recent system they=
 have operated on, without jacking out.</p>
<p>A hacker is in the most recent system they have operated on, without jac=
king out. So if I just hacked the camera computer, that is the system I am =
in. A hacker on their action can move between any controlled connected node=
s freely before taking an action. If the hacker is acting normally (not in =
a trance) then at any time on their turn they can pull the plug and jack ou=
t, severing any connections. If they are instead in a trance, they have to =
get their conscious back to wherever they first entered from (physical jack=
, wifi, or public net). Assuming that path back is all along controlled sys=
tems they can act instantly. If it isn=92t they have to spend turns gain ac=
cess to the nodes in the way. Alternatively while in a trance, they can jus=
t jack out, but suffer 2D10 non-lethal fatigue damage. Also if they are eve=
r incapacitated while being in a trance, they will also jack out immediatel=
y without further consequences.</p>
<p>Each connection is either bi-directional, or controlling. If the connect=
ion is bi-directional, you can get from either node to the other, and contr=
olling the node on one side, does not help you control the other. If the co=
nnection is controlling, they one system is able to send orders to the othe=
r, meaning that if you control that node, you also can give orders to the d=
ownstream node, or access it without a check.</p>
<p>Each node or hacker that you try to act on has a firewall rating, which =
is the target number for most hacking actions. There are then modifiers dep=
ending on how you are accessing the node which are applied to your roll. Se=
e the following tables.</p>
